📄 External Track & Trace System Documentation

(Conserto → Connexis Integration)


---

1. Introduction

The External Track & Trace system is designed to enable real-time tracking and synchronization of transaction lifecycle between Conserto (CST) and Connexis (CXT).

In the previous architecture, UV (iVision) acted as an intermediary system responsible for initiating transactions and sending updates to Connexis. This dependency caused multiple issues such as delayed updates, lack of intermediate visibility, and inconsistent transaction handling.

To address these challenges, a new architecture was introduced where Conserto directly communicates with Connexis, ensuring faster processing, better visibility, and improved system reliability.


---

2. System Objective

The primary goal of this system is to:

Provide real-time and intermediate status visibility

Eliminate dependency on UV for transaction initiation

Ensure consistent and standardized data exchange

Prevent duplicate transaction creation

Enable end-to-end automation of transaction lifecycle



---

3. System Architecture Overview

The system follows an event-driven architecture, where each transaction step is treated as an event.

Key Components

Conserto (CST) – Core system where events are created and processed

Connexis (CXT) – External system that displays transaction tracking

UV Referential API – Provides customer-related data

Camunda Workflow Engine – Controls execution flow

Database Layer – Stores mapping, tracking, and history



---

4. Data Model & Database Design

The system relies on a data-driven design, where logic is controlled through database tables instead of hardcoding.

Core Tables

DPW_EVENT – Stores event-level transaction data

DPW_REQUEST – Stores request-level data


These tables contain critical fields such as:

Event ID

Connexis Reference ID

Transaction ID

Product and status codes

Customer details



---

Track & Trace Tables

DPW_EXTERNAL_TRACK_AND_TRACE – Stores event-level tracking data

DPW_EXTERNAL_TRACK_AND_TRACE_HISTORY – Stores status history

DPW_EXTERNAL_TRACK_AND_TRACE_HISTORY_AUD – Maintains audit logs


These tables ensure:

Traceability of transactions

Prevention of duplicate sending

Full audit tracking



---

Mapping Table (Core Logic Driver)

DPW_EXTERNAL_TRACK_TRACE_MAPPING is the most critical component of the system.

It defines:

Mapping between Conserto and Connexis statuses

Product and transaction codes

Rules for XML generation


Instead of hardcoding logic, the system dynamically fetches values from this table, making it scalable and flexible.


---

5. Customer Data Synchronization

Customer data is fetched from the UV Referential API and updated in the system.

Fields Updated

EB Customer Flag

EB Customer ID

EB Bank ID


This synchronization happens:

At event creation

When customer data is updated


This ensures that only eligible customers trigger Track & Trace processing.


---

6. Core Processing Flow

The system execution begins when a user performs an action.

Step 1: Validate Trigger

When the user clicks the Validate button, the system initiates the Track & Trace process.


---

Step 2: Condition Check

Before processing, the system validates:

Transaction is not an update (is_update = N)

Customer is eligible (eb_cus_flag = Y)

Mapping exists for the current status

Status has not already been sent


Additionally, the system blocks execution if:

Status is Sending (02)

AND transaction ID is NULL


This prevents duplicate transaction creation.


---

Step 3: Mapping Evaluation

The system queries the mapping table using:

Current event status

Action type


If a match is found:

Required fields are extracted

XML generation process starts


If no mapping exists:

The process is stopped



---

Step 4: Camunda Workflow Execution

Once conditions are satisfied, a Camunda workflow is triggered.

The workflow performs:

1. XML generation


2. TAR file creation


3. Status update




